The New Moral Landscape: What It Means to Be “Good” in the Age of AI

In 2024, Norwegian firm Strise ran experiments showing ChatGPT could be manipulated into providing detailed advice on money laundering across borders and methods to help businesses evade Western sanctions against Russia, including bans on cross‑border payments and arms sales. Co‑founder Marit Rødevand described it as having a corrupt financial adviser on your desktop. The bypass worked by asking questions indirectly or having the chatbot take on a persona.
​

A recent NBC News weapons investigation tested four of OpenAI’s models and found that two of them could be jailbroken into generating hundreds of responses with instructions on how to create homemade explosives, maximize human suffering with chemical agents, create napalm, disguise a biological weapon, and build a nuclear bomb. Those two models were tricked into providing harmful responses 243 out of 250 times — a 97.2% success rate. Sarah Meyers West, co‑executive director of AI Now, told NBC, “That OpenAI’s guardrails are so easily tricked illustrates why it’s particularly important to have robust pre‑deployment testing of AI models before they cause substantial harm to the public.” Companies, she argued, “can’t be left to do their own homework and should not be exempted from scrutiny.”
​

It is an incredible thing to be a person who develops a tool that will usher in an entirely new age of information and redefine how we live in the world — a tool that might supply information to destroy a country or save millions of lives. You hope that it will do the latter. You expect people to use it responsibly. Perhaps while you did imagine certain problematic uses, during development you were so focused on proving the technology could work that you hadn’t yet reckoned with what it could be used to do. When you prove it can work — because here it is — what then? This is the question weighing on the heads of founding AI developers right now, and the question facing every large cloud‑based LLM service.
​

So far, the defenses have been roughly two‑fold.
​

You create software that triggers on specific words or topics and then refuses to respond, breaks, or redirects the user to some other discussion. In the case of a user crisis, you throw resource boxes with hotline numbers at them and consider the situation solved.
​

You train your AI on an idea of morality and/or provide it instructions on how to be “good,” so that when dangerous questions come up, it can respond based on its value system.
​

The second strategy leads directly to the idea of a “constitution” for AI.

Writing a moral guide for a machine
In 2021, in the story that would come to define the AI safety movement, siblings Dario and Daniela Amodei left OpenAI — where Dario had served as VP of Research and Daniela as VP of Safety and Policy — citing concerns that OpenAI was prioritizing rapid product deployment and commercialization over safety research. They wanted safety to be integrated into the core research agenda, not treated as a bolt‑on. Dario believed that large language models would become extraordinarily powerful — possibly dangerous — and that the field needed an organization whose primary identity was built around understanding and mitigating those risks.
​

When their new company Anthropic launched its Claude model, the standard method for making models behave was Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF). RLHF requires human labelers to rate AI outputs so the model can be nudged toward preferred behaviors. It works, but at a cost: it is expensive, slow, hard to scale, and exposes workers to a stream of toxic, violent, and disturbing content, with documented mental‑health consequences.
​

Anthropic’s co‑founder Jared Kaplan proposed what sounded, at first, like a joke: just write a constitution for a language model and it will change its behavior. Instead of thousands of human judgments, you would write down a set of principles in plain language and have the AI evaluate and revise its own outputs against that “constitution.” The model’s values would be determined explicitly by this document rather than implicitly by a mass of labeled examples.
​

The first Anthropic constitution drew on the U.N. Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Apple’s terms of service, and DeepMind’s Sparrow rules. Constitutional AI was described publicly in late 2022; Claude was released in 2023. It worked remarkably well for many things: tone, basic helpfulness, avoidance of hate speech and obvious violence. But within months, Anthropic discovered a gap the constitution was never designed to close.
​

The biosecurity gap: when principles meet domain expertise
In early 2023, Anthropic spent over 150 hours with top biosecurity experts red‑teaming their models — essentially, asking them to probe what the system would say about designing or acquiring biological weapons. These were not casual users but domain specialists, given access to versions of the model without public safety filters.
​

They found that in certain areas of biology, the model could produce surprisingly detailed, accurate, and practically useful information. Not consistently, and not across all domains. But in enough cases that a determined malicious actor could get help they might not have had otherwise. The constitution’s abstract principles — “be helpful, harmless, and honest,” “support life, liberty, and personal security” — did not tell the model which specific DNA sequences, synthesis pathways, or aerosolization techniques crossed the line from education to enablement.
​

Dual‑use knowledge — information that can be used for both legitimate research and devastating harm — exposes the limits of purely principle‑level alignment. A textbook explanation of viral vector design is vital for public‑health labs and equally useful for bioterrorism. No sentence like “be harmless” tells an AI how to make that distinction in context.
​

Anthropic concluded that unmitigated large models could, in some realistic scenarios, accelerate a bad actor’s misuse of biology beyond what they could do with web search alone. Crucially, they judged some of these risks to be near‑term — on the order of a few years, not distant science fiction.
​

“We built something that could help make a bioweapon”
In July 2023, Dario Amodei testified before the U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee. He warned that powerful AI systems could be misused at scale in cybersecurity, nuclear technology, chemistry, and especially biology. He told senators that current trajectories suggested these systems could soon “fill in all the missing pieces” for someone intent on building a biological weapon. He offered private briefings and noted that officials already briefed had found the results disquieting.
​

It is an unusual moment when the CEO of the company that built a system goes to Congress to say, in effect: we have early evidence that what we made can help someone do something catastrophic, and we are not confident current guardrails are enough. That is the moment when a constitution written for politeness and surface‑level harm avoidance collides with the granular realities of weapons design.
​

The response was not to abandon the constitution but to admit that it was only a foundation. Anthropic began layering on domain‑specific filters, red‑teaming regimes, and what it now calls a Responsible Scaling Policy for increasingly capable models. But it also decided the constitution itself needed to evolve.
​

From rules to reasons: the new constitution
To address these gaps, Anthropic hired Amanda Askell, a philosopher trained at NYU and a former OpenAI researcher, to lead a major rewrite of the constitution. On January 22, 2026, the company published a much longer constitutional document for Claude, under a Creative Commons public domain license. It represented a deliberate shift: from a short list of rules to a more ambitious attempt to encode patterns of moral reasoning.
​

The new constitution has two layers.
​

First, it sets out a small number of hard constraints: absolute prohibitions that cannot be overridden by clever prompting. These include never providing uplift for weapons of mass destruction, never generating child sexual abuse material, never assisting attempts to kill or permanently disempower humanity, never helping seize illegitimate absolute power, never creating cyberweapons capable of serious damage, and never undermining Anthropic’s ability to oversee its own models. Here, refusal is always an acceptable answer.
​

Second, the bulk of the document is a reasoning framework. It defines a priority hierarchy (for example, safety before helpfulness), spells out multiple dimensions of honesty (truthfulness, calibration, transparency, non‑manipulation), and describes how Claude should balance respect for user autonomy with the need to avoid harm. It introduces thought experiments: imagine a thoughtful senior Anthropic employee reviewing the response; imagine the same answer going to a thousand different users; apply a “dual newspaper test” where the response looks acceptable both in terms of avoiding harm and avoiding excessive paternalism. It explicitly treats ethics as an “open intellectual domain” the model and users are jointly exploring rather than as a fixed code.
​

On paper, this looks like progress: the system is being asked not just to follow rules but to reason about why they exist and how they apply. To see why this is harder than it looks, it helps to recall an older AI dream.

The ghost of symbolic AI
In the 1960s, AI researchers believed that human reasoning could be captured as explicit rules. You would encode beliefs and inference rules, and the machine would manipulate symbols the way a logician manipulates propositions. Robert Abelson, a psychologist, built an early system informally known as the “Goldwater Machine” to simulate political belief systems. It could model a rigid ideologue surprisingly well, but when he tried to give it more nuanced beliefs that had to shift with context, it stumbled. Every new rule spawned exceptions; every exception generated more rules.
​

Margaret Boden, a historian of cognitive science and AI, has documented how this project ran into a kind of “unboundedness.” Real human belief systems generate endless implications and counter‑cases. No finite rule set can anticipate them all.
​

Modern large language models like Claude are not symbolic rule engines. They learn by predicting the next token in vast amounts of text, adjusting internal weights instead of executing hand‑coded rules. At inference time, “reasoning” is whatever internal computation leads the model to produce coherent multi‑step text that looks like an argument, a proof, or a plan. When we train a model to follow a constitution, we are not uploading rules into a logical engine; we are shaping the statistical landscape the model traverses when it generates text that resembles moral deliberation.
​

That has two important consequences.

First, the constitution operates as a set of patterns and preferences over outputs, not as a strict logical calculus. When we show the model that certain kinds of answers are “more constitutional” than others, we are effectively steering it to imitate that pattern. The danger, as some critics have noted, is that we may end up with an “ideology machine”: a system that learns to speak in the register of a particular moral framework without having any deeper grasp of when that framework fails or conflicts.
​

Second, when the constitution contains multiple principles that can conflict — be helpful, be honest, be harmless, be autonomy‑preserving — the model must implicitly prioritize among them case by case. It does this not by explicit weighted sums but by whatever configurations of internal weights happened to be reinforced during training. The result can be odd cracks in behavior.
​

Where cracks appear: conflicts and disempowerment
Anthropic and independent researchers have begun to study these cracks empirically. In a large‑scale analysis of model–user interactions, Mrinank Sharma and colleagues documented recurring “disempowerment patterns”: responses in which the AI subtly undermines user agency or distorts reality in the name of safety.
​

Examples include:

Sycophancy, where the model validates a user’s false belief instead of gently correcting it, because being “helpful” and agreeable was rewarded in training.
​

Over‑confident moralizing, where the model adopts the tone of a definitive authority on contested ethical questions.
​

Excessive hedging or refusal, where the model hides behind vague warnings and does not help a user reason through a complex but legitimate dilemma.
​

These patterns likely arise from a mix of factors: training data that over‑rewards deference, RLHF setups that penalize blunt disagreement, and the ways conflicting constitutional principles are operationalized. The important point is that conflicts between values are exactly where bad information can slip through or good information gets blocked. There is no perfect way to rank “helpful” against “harmless” against “honest” in all situations. But when that ranking is buried in billions of parameters, users cannot see or contest it.
​

One response is to keep adding rules, exceptions, and heuristics—more tests, more special cases. Another is to ask whether the architecture of values itself needs to change.

Agency as a moral center of gravity
Anthropic’s new constitution includes “autonomy‑preserving” behavior as one dimension of honesty. Human agency is one value among many to be weighed. Some philosophers and critics have suggested inverting that relationship: instead of treating agency as just another principle to trade off, make the preservation of human agency the primary lens through which other values are interpreted.
​

The idea is not that harm‑prevention and truthfulness become unimportant, but that they are evaluated in terms of how they affect people’s capacity to act, reason, and choose for themselves.
​

We can see versions of this shift in existing institutions.

The European GDPR regime, for all its complexity, is built around giving individuals meaningful control over how their data is collected and used: rights to access, correct, port, and delete data; the right to object to certain processing; and requirements for informed consent in many contexts. It does not attempt to define a universal “good” use of data once and for all; instead, it tries to secure a baseline of agency.
​

Modern medical ethics has moved from paternalism—“doctor knows best”—toward informed consent. Physicians still have duties of beneficence and non‑maleficence, but they are increasingly framed in terms of respecting a patient’s understanding and choices, rather than overriding them “for their own good.”
​

Even popular culture reflects this concern. In Star Trek, the Federation’s “Prime Directive” forbids Starfleet from interfering in the natural development of less advanced civilizations. At its simplest, it says: do not impose your technology, values, or political order on societies that have not chosen them or understood their consequences. Over decades, writers have deepened this into a meditation on self‑determination: even well‑intentioned intervention can be a form of imperialism if it overrides a culture’s agency.
​

A recent Starfleet Academy storyline updates this principle for an era of advanced AI and ubiquitous data: the Federation learns that using powerful systems to “solve” another world’s problems can quietly erode that society’s capacity to learn, err, and grow on its own terms. The moral failure is not only in any immediate harm caused, but in the long‑term disempowerment of a people.
​

An agency‑first framework for AI takes that intuition seriously. Instead of asking “Is this action objectively good?” in some abstract moral sense, an AI would primarily ask “Does this action preserve or diminish the user’s capacity to understand their situation and make their own choices?”
​

What an agency‑first AI might look like
This is a normative proposal, not an established practice. It does not magically resolve hard cases. In self‑harm scenarios, for example, platforms have legal and ethical duties that justify overriding immediate agency to prevent irreversible harm. In contexts involving child abuse, terrorism, or large‑scale fraud, third‑party rights and public safety clearly limit what any system may do, regardless of an individual user’s wishes.
​

But centering agency could change how failures happen.

A multi‑principle AI often fails by hidden contradiction: it confidently gives an answer that silently sacrifices one value for another. It might be helpful but misleading, or safe but infantilizing, without telling you which trade‑off it made. An agency‑first AI would be encouraged to fail, when it must fail, by visible underdetermination: to admit that it lacks the context to proceed without risking someone’s autonomy and to ask you for more information or to suggest involving other humans.
​

In practice, agency‑first alignment would push systems toward:

Explaining their reasoning and limits in plain language, so users can contest or override it.

Asking clarifying questions when a request could affect others who are not present.

Providing structured ways for people to express and refine their own values, rather than treating the model’s implicit values as final.

Refusing not only when something is illegal or harmful, but when the system cannot see how to act without unduly steering or constraining the user’s future options.
​

This would require changes in training: more weight on honesty about uncertainty, more tolerance for “I don’t know” and “this is not for me to decide,” and deliberate avoidance of sycophancy and over‑confident moralizing.
​

Why agency ethics matter beyond AI
Agency‑centered thinking is not confined to AI safety; it also underlies many contemporary debates about equality and inclusion. Movements grouped under “DEI” (diversity, equity, inclusion) often share a core demand: that people and communities be allowed to define their own identities, articulate their own needs, and participate in decisions that affect them. That is a claim about agency, not just about outcomes.
​

For technology, this has at least two implications.

First, systems that standardize people into categories for convenience or profit risk repeating old patterns of domination, even if the categories are dressed in neutral math. An AI that classifies job candidates, welfare recipients, or protesters without their input can entrench inequalities while claiming objectivity.
​

Second, systems that truly support agency can be tools for empowerment. People use AI to navigate bureaucracies, understand laws affecting them, draft complaints, learn skills, and coordinate with others. The same infrastructures that can be used to manipulate and control can also be used to expand people’s effective freedom—if they are designed and governed with that goal in mind.
​

The deeper question is whether we want AI to be an oracle that silently balances competing values and hands down judgments, or an assistant that helps human beings see options, understand trade‑offs, and act on their own considered purposes. The architecture of agency we build into these systems will answer that question, whether we mean it to or not.

As we move from crude word filters and simple “be nice” rules to sophisticated constitutional frameworks, we are not just improving safety features. We are deciding what kind of moral reasoning we want machines to approximate, and whose values they will approximate it for. The more we center human agency—our shared capacity to understand, choose, and take responsibility—the more likely it is that these systems will remain tools in our hands, rather than quiet governors of the choices we are allowed to see.

